description: DCAT dataset entries.
Local database identifier of the dataset.
A type belonging to the record
A name given to the record.
A free-text account of the item.
A keyword or tag describing the resource.

A language of the item. This refers to the natural language used for textual metadata (i.e. titles, descriptions, etc) of a cataloged resource (i.e. dataset or service) or the textual values of a dataset distribution.
A web page which can be navigated to using a web browser to access the records.
A related object that references that points to this item.
An object with an unspecified relation to this item.
Links to a description of a relationship with another resource.
Describes an entity that is in some form responsible for the item but is neither a creator or publisher.
A main category of the resource. A resource can have multiple themes.
Relevant contact information for the cataloged resource. Use of vCard is recommended [VCARD-RDF].
The entity responsible for producing the resource.
The entity responsible for publishing the resource.
A legal document under which the resource is made available.
A statement that concerns all rights not addressed with dct:license or dct:accessRights, such as copyright statements.
Information about who can access the resource or an indication of its security status (DCAT-AP: Whether item is publicly accessible, has access restrictions or is not public).

description: The rights described as an ODRL conformant policy.
Formal date of publication.
Most recent date of modification.
The version of the item.
Refers to an item which is the previous version of this item.
Used with an abstract item to refer to all items which represent different versions of this abstract item.
Used with an abstract item to refer to the item that represents the current version of this abstract item.
A related item that is superseded by this item.
A changelog regarding the differences between this version and the previous one.
The status of this item. Does not enforce a specific standard, though using existing standards such as "EU Vocabularies Distribution Status" is adviced.
An object that is included in this item.
The first item in an ordered collection this item belongs to (when using dcat:DataSeries).
The last item in an ordered collection this item belongs to (when using dcat:DataSeries).
The previous item in an ordered collection this item belongs to (when using dcat:DataSeries).
A distribution belonging to this item.
The frequency at which dataset is published.
A series this item belongs to.
The geographical area covered by the dataset.
Minimum spatial separation resolvable in a dataset, measured in meters.
The temporal period that the dataset covers.
Minimum time period resolvable in the dataset.
An activity that generated, or provides the business context for, the creation of the dataset.
Legislation that mandates creation or management of this item (must follow European Legislation Identifier (ELI) guidelines).
A page or document about this item.
A secondary identifier of the item (f.e. DOI, W3ID, etc).
A statement about the lineage of the item.
A sample distribution of this item.
A related item from which the this item is derived.
This property must be attached to every entity that you wish the EJP-RD Virtual Platform to explore.
The act of making data or other structured information accessible to the public or to the user group of a database.
One or more characters used to identify, name, or characterize the nature, properties, or contents of a thing.
The words or language units by which a thing is known.
A written or verbal account, representation, statement, or explanation of something.
A date of database submission refers to the moment in time in which some information was submitted/received to a database system.
Indicates the person or authoritative body who brought the item into existence.
The person or authoritative body who provided the information.
A notation regarding the decisions, and/or clarification of any information pertaining to data management.

container of files belonging together (different datasets can contain overlapping files, except for the intial datasets containing startfiles (before analysis, startfiles= BAM, gVCF files (one per chromosome) and phenopacket file))
One or more characters used to identify, name, or characterize the nature, properties, or contents of a thing.
A written or verbal account, representation, statement, or explanation of something.
Data use modifiers indicate additional conditions for use. For instance, a dataset is restricted to investigations into specific diseases or performed at specific geographical locations.
type of dataset (raw or processed (analysed) data)
A written explanation, observation or criticism added to textual material.
